{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 13:47:22.718269", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall network health appears good. OSPF adjacencies are up and stable, routing is present end-to-end, DHCP provided leases to both user hosts, DNS resolves internal names, and HTTP services (web0.local–web3.local and the load balancer web99.local) are reachable from host subnets.\n- The backend network behind the load balancer (20.200.0.0/24) is not advertised in OSPF, enforcing the design that backend servers are not directly reachable from hosts.\n- Minor observations: a single netstat timeout on the load balancer (service is running and reachable), and cosmetic OSPF next-hop formatting on dist routers.\n\nKey findings and evidence\n\n1) Host addressing and basic reachability\n- host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.10/24 via 10.1.1.1 (DHCP, valid_lft ~60s)\n- host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.10/24 via 10.2.1.1 (DHCP, valid_lft ~36s)\n- L3 reachability:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> router_dist_1_1 (172.16.0.7): OK\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> router_dist_2_1 (172.16.0.9): OK\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> host_2_1_1_1: OK (low RTTs)\n- DHCP appears functional given dynamic addresses and valid lease timers on both hosts.\n\n2) OSPF control-plane status\n- All FRR routers report Full neighbor relationships consistent with the topology:\n  - Core triangle: core_1, core_2, core_3 all Full with each other on area 0 links.\n  - Dist-to-core: dist_1_1 Full to core_1 on 172.16.0.6/31 (area 1); dist_2_1 Full to core_2 on 172.16.0.8/31 (area 1).\n  - Server access: server_access_router Full to core_3 on 172.16.0.10/31 (area 0).\n- OSPF routes present across the fabric:\n  - Core routers have OSPF routes to 10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, and 10.200.0.0/24 via expected neighbors.\n  - server_access_router has OSPF routes to both user subnets via core_3 (172.16.0.10/31).\n  - Distribution routers have OSPF routes to the server VLAN (10.200.0.0/24) via their core uplinks.\n\n3) Server access router and server VLAN\n- server_access_router bridges eth0–eth6 into br0 with IP 10.200.0.1/24; OSPF advertises 10.200.0.0/24 in area 0.\n- IP routing on server_access_router shows learned routes to users’ subnets via core_3 and connected server VLAN on br0.\n\n4) DNS service\n- dns_server has 10.200.0.2/24 with default GW 10.200.0.1.\n- netstat shows named listening on 10.200.0.2:53 (UDP/TCP) and 127.0.0.1:53.\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2 ICMP: OK; HTTP name lookups for local zone names completed quickly in curl tests, indicating DNS is serving clients.\n\n5) Web and load balancing services\n- web_server_0..3 each listen on TCP/80 and are reachable:\n  - From host_1_1_1_1, HTTP to web0.local–web3.local succeeds; TTFB ~0.18–0.41s, total ~1.0–1.2s.\n- load_balancer (nginx) status: active (running).\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.7 ICMP: OK.\n  - HTTP to web99.local and to 10.200.0.7 succeeds; TTFB ~0.21–0.31s, total ~1.0–1.1s.\n- load_balancer has eth1 on 20.200.0.1/24; this backend subnet is not present in OSPF, aligning with the design that backends are not directly reachable from hosts.\n\n6) Policy/isolation validation (backend servers not directly reachable)\n- OSPF advertisements do not include 20.200.0.0/24 on any router but the load balancer’s local interface. Distribution and core routers only carry 10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, and 10.200.0.0/24—no route to 20.200.0.0/24 exists in the fabric. This enforces backend isolation by routing.\n\nNotable anomalies or irregularities\n- Tool timeout on load_balancer for netstat: One attempt exceeded 10s. Cross-checks show nginx is active and HTTP works from clients. Likely a transient or tooling issue rather than a service failure.\n- OSPF route display on distribution routers shows next-hop as their own local P2P address (e.g., “via 172.16.0.6” on router_dist_1_1). Despite this cosmetic oddity, adjacencies, routing, and data-plane forwarding are correct end-to-end. This appears to be a display quirk on point-to-point links rather than a forwarding anomaly.\n\nPerformance observations\n- HTTP timing from host_1_1_1_1 shows TTFB ~0.2–0.4s with total ~1.0–1.2s across direct web servers and the load balancer. Given low ICMP RTTs and consistent TTFB, the additional ~0.6–0.9s likely reflects application payload transfer rather than a network path issue. No packet loss observed in pings.\n\nConclusion\n- No critical anomalies detected. The network forwarding plane and OSPF control plane are operating as designed: hosts have addresses via DHCP, can resolve names via the DNS in 10.200.0.0/24, and can reach the Apache web servers and the Nginx load balancer. The backend network remains non-advertised and isolated from hosts per design. Minor tooling/formatting quirks were noted but do not indicate functional issues.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 21501, "output_tokens": 5211, "total_tokens": 26712, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 19456}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3776}}}
